entry.title: immersive fullscreen: prevent DCHECK on fullscreen exit
entry.content:
If popup is active during immersive fullscreen exit, a DCHECK can be

triggered if the timing is right.



[native_widget_ns_window_bridge.mm(1717)] Check failed: 0u == CountBridgedWindows([window_ childWindows]) (0 vs. 1)



ImmersiveModeTabbedControllerCocoa::OrderTabWindowZOrderOnTop is being

called during fullscreen exit. If it runs after the overlay window has

removed all its children, the tab window will re-add itself as a child

of the overlay window, throwing off the counts in

NativeWidgetNSWindowBridge::OnVisibilityChanged.



This CL prevents the miscount by preventing the tab window from

re-adding itself as a child of the overlay window if it is not current a

child of the overlay window.

of the overlay and tab overlay windows to tell them apart easier. I have

included these descriptions in this CL for debug builds. Here is what

they look like:



(lldb) po [NSApp windows]

<__NSArrayM 0x600000366c10>(

- New Tab,

- overlay,

- tab overlay,

,

entry.title: heap: Remove Blink's GCTaskRunner
entry.content:
Note: This change does not affect production semantics of garbage

collection.



Safepoint support was necessary in the initial implementation of

Oilpan (anno 2015) to run stack-less GCs in a timely fashion. The

safepoint mechanism uses task observers and as such hooks into _every_

task that was executed on the main thread. This completely bypassed

the scheduler and any heuristics it may have to meet deadlines.



These days the GCs are all triggered through unified heap in V8.

Asynchronous GCs (== stack-less GC) are implemented via scheduling

non-nestable tasks through `PostNonNestableTask()` for GC

finalizations.



The safepoint hook was still used to perform stack-less GCs after JS

`gc()` intrinsic calls in testing scenarios. These days these are

better written using `asyncGC()` (in web tests) and using the advanced

options for the `gc()` intrinsic that allow for awaitable async GC

otherwise (using `await gc({type: 'major', execution: 'async'})`).



A small side effect of this is that we also make prod faster by

removing a task observer that was otherwise always present.

entry.title: Remove non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_
entry.content:
Previously, `NavigationURLLoaderImpl`

- Created all per-scheme `mojo::Remote` for known schemes in

`non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_`, and then

- Created a `WeakWrapperSharedURLLoaderFactory` connecting to the

per-scheme `mojo::Remote` upon a request for the scheme.



This CL

- Creates a `SharedURLLoaderFactory` upon a request for the scheme,

- Caches and reuses it via `non_network_url_loader_factories_`, and

- Avoids creating per-scheme factories/Remotes unless actually used.

- Changes the name and signature of `ContentBrowserClient`'s

`RegisterNonNetworkNavigationURLLoaderFactories`

to `CreateNonNetworkNavigationURLLoaderFactory` to align with the

new factory creation model.



This is to

- Simplify the logic by always using `url_loader_factory::Create()`

and removing a `url_loader_factory::GetTestingInterceptor()` call.

- Simplify the lifetime.

Previously, `NavigationURLLoaderImpl::url_loader_` had a raw

reference to

`NavigationURLLoaderImpl::non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_`

via `WeakWrapperSharedURLLoaderFactory`, and thus there was a

deconstruction order dependency between these two members.

This CL removes this dependency, and now

`GetOrCreateNonNetworkLoaderFactory()` and its returned factory

can be used without carefully considering the lifetime of

`NavigationURLLoaderImpl`.

entry.title: Make the ADM and PayDM observe the WebDataService
entry.content:
The PDM currently implements AutofillWebDataServiceObserverOnUISequence

and observes the (or rather both) AutofillWebDataService. It gets

notified whenever the database was changed from the sync side,

triggering PDM::OnAutofillChangedBySync(model_type), which causes a

Refresh().

This Refresh() reloads all data, independently of the model_type that

has changed.



This CL removes the PDM's observer and instead adds observers from the

from the ADM and from the PayDM. (Since the ADM only cares about the

on-disk database, it only observes one WebDataService. The PayDM cares

about both). When their OnAutofillChangedBySync() is called, they only

start reload if data related to their model types has changed (this is a

behavior change).



This untangle part of the dependency mess introduced by [1]. By doing

so, CancelPendingServerQueries() can move into the PayDM, and the

PaymentsDatabaseHelper no longer needs to depend on the PDM.

Finally, instead of canceling queries from the PDM destructor, the logic

is moved to the ADM and PayDM destructors.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5310378/comment/35d3cadb_05cf168e/

entry.title: Fix TTL handling for alias-form HTTPS records
entry.content:
While these records are mostly ignored because Chrome doesn't yet

handle following the aliases, they still count for triggering

http->https upgrade and thus still get merged into cached results via

an empty metadata result. But we weren't using them to calculate the

expiration for the HTTPS response and the calculated expiration for a

response containing only an alias was base::Time::Max(). Not really a

problem with HostCache because it'll almost always get combined with

the lower expirations from address results, but creates a problem for

the new HostResolverCache where HTTPS results get cached separately.



To fix, calculate expiration from all "compatible" records (those

records that count for triggering http->https upgrade) when an empty-

metadata result is created. Otherwise, continue using TTLs only from

records of use to Chrome.

entry.title: Split payments DB reading logic from PDM to new PaymentsDataManager
entry.content:
Creates a new PaymentsDataManager class and moves the following logic

from the PDM into it without changes:

- Querying the WebDataService and receiving the results by implementing

WebDataServiceConsumer.

Since address reading logic was already moved into the ADM, the PDM

now no longer needs to implement WebDataServiceConsumer.

Ever since crrev.com/c/5290994, this won't cause problems with

observers anymore.

- Storing the results from the database. All members such as

local_credit_cards_ and server_credit_cards_ are moved to the

PaymentsDataManager.

Since the writing logic is still in the PDM, the PaymentsDataManager

declares the PDM as a friend, so it can access these members. This

amounts to most of the changes in personal_data_manager.cc and

test_personal_data_manager.cc (i.e. prefixing the access to a member

with payments_data_manager_->).

- Switching between on-disk and in-memory DB: With Butter4Payments, an

in-memory database is used for server data. Currently,

PersonalDatabaseHelper, a helper class of the PDM is responsible for

deciding which DB to use. This class is moved and renamed to

PaymentsDatabaseHelper. This is done in the same CL, since querying

the database requires referencing the database.

- Cart art fetching is kept in the PDM for now, since they are not

coming from the database.



The PaymentsDataManager is owned by the PDM.



This moves quite a bit of code, since payments has several different

data types (cards, IBANs, offers, etc).



No behavior changes.

entry.title: [UNO] Support Sign in paused - PeopleHandler
entry.content:
With Uno the primary account should be set/cleared with explicit user

action.



The people handler on signout:

- Shows Gaia logout tab

- If a primary account with sync still exists, it invokes sync.



This relies on:

- In case of signin primary account,

`DiceResponseHandler::ProcessDiceSignoutHeader` will revoke all

tokens on signout.

- On revoke sync consent, the `SigninManager` will clear all accounts if

the accounts in the Gaia cookie is empty (/Logout).



These assumptions will be broken on follow-up CLs with:

- `SigninManager` no longer created in the Full Uno experiment

- Signout from the web only invalidated the primary account.



This CL ensures on Signout from Chrome Setting, the primary account is

removed. On next reconciliation cycle, the `AccountReconcilor` will

match the refresh tokens to the accounts in the Gaia cookie. As the

\Logout + \ListAccounts are network requests, it is expected the account

reconcilor will run after the primary account is removed.

entry.title: [Android TRM] Fix crash from bad ModuleDelegate calls.
entry.content:
The Magic Stack callbacks

onDataReady()

onDataFetchFailed()



helps the framework decide whether or not to show a module. For each

module there should only be one invocation total.



Tab Resumption Module's recently integrated with Magic Stack, but didn't

follow the above constraint. Direct causes:

1. ForeignSessionTabResumptionDataProvider: The ForeignSessionHelper use

followed "Recent Tab" feature's example of doing both sync (to read

cached data if no new data) and async (to receive new data if

available) reads. Thus read and downstream updates can happen twice.

In some cases, both callbacks above are invoked (e.g., initially no

foreign tabs exist, then open NTP 1, then new foreign tab is opened,

then open NTP 2).

* The async listener can fire for later updates. This is undesirable

since the TRM currently does have dynamic refresh, except for

handling login / sync status changes.

2. TabResumptionModuleMediator: loadModule() naively calls onDataReady()

when suggestions are available, and onDataFetchFailed() otherwise;

there's no restrictions on repeated callback invocation.

* These calls happen after processing and rendering -- it might be

more efficient to call earlier.



Meanwhile, here's an existing Magic Stack issue:

3. If a module calls onDataFetchFailed(), it gets hidden, but there's

no guarantee that cleanup (via hideModule()) gets executed, even

after NTP closes (despite crrev.com/5304099).



The above combine to cause a crashing bug:



(3) causes ForeignSessionTabResumptionDataProvider to leak, along with a

stale HomeModulesMediator. From (1), the async data listener is active,

and it fires if a remote tabs updates happens and another NTP opens.

From (2), onDataReady() gets called, causing stale HomeModulesMediator

retrieve empty data, resulting in null object reference.



Fixing any of the above would prevent the crash, but it's best to

address them all. This CL makes simple fixes to (1) and (2):

* ForeignSessionTabResumptionDataProvider: Remove async load. This

solution also avoids downstream processing complexity, although the

TRM becomes less responsive to updates, since new data fetched from

triggerSessionSync() is likely unavailable to getForeignSessions()

call for the current module. Removing async load also prevents

multiple async updates.

* TabResumptionModuleMediator: Add |mHasPreviousLoad| to ensure that the

callbacks are only called once. Also move the call before render.



Issue (3) will be fixed separately by hanxi@.

entry.title: Fuzzing coverage timing & retry tweaks.
entry.content:
The fuzzing coverage dashboard currently takes 4.8 hours to run all the

fuzzers, but fails to gather coverage for the MojoLPM fuzzers. This CL

is an attempt to adjust some of the timeouts and retry limits to

(hopefully) achieve better coverage collection within the same sort of

time limit.



The overall algorithm (unchanged) is:

* Try to run the fuzzer against its whole corpus, retrying

* If that doesn't work, run it against individual test cases, until

we've gathered 'n' traces successfully, or attempted 'm' traces



This CL:

* Increases 'n' from 10 to 100. This is what seems to be needed to

gather coverage from most of our MojoLPM fuzzers. (100 is just a

guess). This will obviously increase the time taken for the job.

* Decreases 'm' from 1000 to 500, which will save some time but will

likely only impact two fuzzers, so won't save much.

* Decreases the retries on the initial whole-corpus run from 2 to 1

because there's no evidence that retries actually help anyway.

* Decreases the timeout for each individual-test-case run from 30

minutes to 1 minute. I don't think we're currently hitting this

timeout so this probably won't make any difference.

* Decreases the timeout for the whole-corpus run from 30 minutes

to 20 minutes. This is being hit 67 times at the moment - it's

not clear whether this is because these fuzzers are stalled or

because it's just taking a long time to run them. So this is a

bit of a gamble - this could reduce overall execution time (if the

former) or increase it (if the latter, and we then have to run

more test cases individually.)

constructing all of the main components and injecting the right

dependencies. When created, the CertificateProvisioningService will

entry.title: Add GPU host_information
entry.content:
Adds a host_information module used for determining information

about the host that the Python test harness is running on. This

is meant for use cases where a browser is not available to pull

tags from. Since this is specifically for the host, it does not

work for remote platforms such as Android or ChromeOS.



Currently, OS type, CPU architecture, and GPU vendor are

supported information.



Concrete list of changes:

1. Adds the host_information module

2. Adds an info_collection test case to verify that the

information provided by this module matches what is provided

by the browser.

3. Changes most existing uses of sys.platform to use

host_information instead.

4. Makes use of CPU and GPU information to restrict test

serializations to only the configurations that actually

need them.

entry.title: Prevent crash calling setDeviceMetricsOverride on autoresize window
entry.content:
Emulation.setDeviceMetricsOverride goes through a series of calls

leading to WebFrameWidgetImpl::SetScreenInfoAndSize, which has a DCHECK

for frames with autoresize enabled. This change returns an early error

to avoid getting to the DCHECK and crashing.



Emulation.canEmulate already returns false in this case, so another

solution would be to simply block all commands in the domain. However,

most of the domain does work, so this felt unnecessarily restrictive.



This change is being made in anticipation of future changes that will

make extension popups (which have autoresize enabled) more consistently

show as pages in CDP, therefore increasing the likelihood commands are

called.
